    {
      "id": "q8",
      "type": "numeric",
      "promptTex": "\\text{Smallest positive solution of } \\sin x + \\sqrt{3}\\cos x = 1 \\text{ (in radians; round 2 decimals)?}",
      "answer": 1.57,
      "tolerance": 0.05,
      "hints": [
        "Rewrite: $\\sin x + \\sqrt{3}\\cos x = 2(\\sin x \\cdot 1/2 + \\cos x \\cdot \\sqrt{3}/2) = 2\\sin(x + \\pi/3)$.",
        "$2\\sin(x + \\pi/3) = 1 \\Rightarrow \\sin(x + \\pi/3) = 1/2$.",
        "$x + \\pi/3 = \\pi/6$ or $5\\pi/6$. So $x = -\\pi/6$ or $\\pi/2$. Smallest positive: $\\pi/2 \\approx 1.57$."
      ],
      "explanation": "Rewrite as $2\\sin(x + \\pi/3) = 1$. Then $\\sin(x + \\pi/3) = 1/2$, giving $x + \\pi/3 = \\pi/6$ or $5\\pi/6$. So $x = -\\pi/6$ or $\\pi/2$. Smallest positive: $\\pi/2 \\approx 1.57$.",
      "steps": [
        {
          "text": "**Rewrite the LHS as a single sinusoid.** With $a = 1, b = \\sqrt{3}$, amplitude $\\sqrt{a^2 + b^2} = 2$."
        },
        {
          "math": "\\sin x + \\sqrt{3}\\cos x = 2\\left(\\dfrac{1}{2}\\sin x + \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\cos x\\right) = 2\\sin(x + \\pi/3)"
        },
        {
          "text": "**Set equal to 1:**"
        },
        {
          "math": "2\\sin(x + \\pi/3) = 1 \\;\\Longrightarrow\\; \\sin(x + \\pi/3) = \\dfrac{1}{2}"
        },
        {
          "text": "**General solution:** $x + \\pi/3 = n\\pi + (-1)^n \\pi/6$."
        },
        {
          "text": "$n = 0$: $x + \\pi/3 = \\pi/6 \\Rightarrow x = -\\pi/6$ (negative)."
        },
        {
          "text": "$n = 1$: $x + \\pi/3 = \\pi - \\pi/6 = 5\\pi/6 \\Rightarrow x = \\pi/2 \\approx 1.57$."
        },
        {
          "text": "**Smallest positive: $x = \\pi/2 \\approx 1.57$.**"
        }
      ],
      "difficulty": "hard"
    },
